  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers sign a Form 6 authority with their real estate agent and give the disclosure section little more than a passing glance. In the vast majority of transactions, that section is blank and the question is academic. But understanding what an agent is legally required to disclose, and what happens if they do not, is useful knowledge for any seller entering an agency agreement in Queensland.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal framework: Property Occupations Act 2014</h2>
      <p>Queensland's Property Occupations Act 2014 requires that a real estate agent disclose any personal, business, or financial interest they hold in a property transaction before the seller signs the Form 6 agency authority. This is a legal obligation, not a professional courtesy, and verbal disclosure is not sufficient. The disclosure must be made in writing.</p>

      <p>The obligation extends to related persons and entities. If the agent's spouse, a business associate, a company in which the agent has an interest, or another related party has an interest in the transaction, that connection must also be disclosed. The definition of a related person under the Act is deliberately broad.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When disclosure is required</h2>
      <p>The most common circumstances that trigger the disclosure obligation are:</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent or a related person is a potential buyer.</strong> If the agent, their spouse, a business partner, or a company connected to them is considering purchasing the property, that interest must be disclosed in writing before the Form 6 is signed.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent receives a benefit from a third party connected to the transaction.</strong> If the agent receives a referral fee from a buyer's agent, a financial planner directing clients to purchase the property, or any other third party with an interest in the outcome, that benefit must be disclosed.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent has a financial interest in the buyer's business.</strong> If the agent holds shares in, or receives income from, a business owned by the prospective buyer, the connection must be disclosed.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent is related to the buyer.</strong> Family relationships between the agent and a prospective buyer constitute an interest that must be disclosed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Consequences of non-disclosure</h2>
      <p>If an agent fails to make a required disclosure before the Form 6 is signed, the consequences can be significant. The agency authority may be voidable at the seller's election, which means the seller may have grounds to walk away from the agreement. The agent may face disciplinary action through the Office of Fair Trading, including fines, licence suspension, or cancellation depending on the severity of the breach. The seller may also have grounds for a formal complaint or, in serious cases, a civil claim.</p>

      <p>Non-disclosure does not automatically void the authority or cancel the transaction, but it gives the seller legal standing to challenge both. A seller who discovers mid-campaign that their agent had an undisclosed interest in the outcome should seek legal advice promptly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do at the Form 6 stage</h2>
      <p>Before signing the Form 6, read the disclosure of interest section carefully. If it is left blank, that is the standard position for most transactions, and no further action is required. If the agent has completed the disclosure section, take the time to understand what is being disclosed and whether the disclosed interest creates a genuine conflict with your goals as a seller.</p>

      <p>In most cases where a disclosure is made, it is routine and the agent can still act effectively for you. An agent who discloses that they are referring buyers from a particular buyer's advocate, for example, is not necessarily compromised. The issue arises when the disclosed interest is likely to affect the agent's conduct in ways that do not serve your interests, most commonly when the agent or a connected party has a financial stake in who purchases the property or at what price.</p>

      <p>If a disclosure gives you pause, the right question to ask is whether the agent can genuinely prioritise your outcome as a seller given the interest they have disclosed. If the answer is not clearly yes, you are entitled to decline to appoint that agent and seek representation elsewhere.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Dual agency: when the same agency acts for buyer and seller</h2>
      <p>A related issue is dual agency, where the selling agent and the buyer's agent work for the same real estate business. This is not prohibited in Queensland, but it creates an inherent tension. An agent acting for both parties cannot fully advocate for either without compromising the other. When this situation arises, the agent has an obligation to disclose it, and the seller should clearly instruct the agent in writing about whose interests take priority.</p>

      <p>Sellers who find themselves in a dual agency situation should at minimum confirm with their agent in writing that the agent's primary obligation is to achieve the best possible price for the seller, and that the internal buyer's agent relationship will not influence the campaign, the negotiation, or the recommendation to accept any particular offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical starting point</h2>
      <p>The Form 6 is a legally binding document. Reading it carefully before you sign, including the disclosure section, the commission terms, and the duration of the exclusive agency period, is one of the most straightforward protections available to you as a seller. Most transactions in Queensland proceed without any disclosure issues at all. But knowing what the obligations are means you are in a position to recognise when something does not look right, and to ask the questions that protect your interests before you are committed.</p>

